# Visual thinking

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Visual Thinking is a methodology that employs visual aids and graphical representations to facilitate understanding, communication, and problem-solving in collaborative settings.

## Purpose
The primary purpose of Visual Thinking is to improve clarity and foster deeper engagement in discussions, brainstorming sessions, and decision-making processes by making complex information more accessible and enhancing cognitive processing.

## How it works
Visual Thinking involves identifying key concepts or ideas, choosing the right visual tools or techniques, creating initial sketches or diagrams, facilitating a discussion or workshop using the visuals, and refining and iterating on the visuals based on feedback and new ideas generated during the session.

## Requirements
Basic drawing or sketching skills, or access to digital visualization tools, understanding of the principles of visual communication and design, and materials for creating visuals are required to effectively use Visual Thinking.

## Reflections
When using Visual Thinking in innovation, it's essential to ensure that visuals simplify concepts rather than complicate them, taking into account any disabilities, cultural appropriateness, and skill levels of the group. Relying too heavily on technology or neglecting other communication methods can also be counterproductive.

## Related methods (if any)
Visual Thinking is often used in conjunction with Design Thinking, facilitation, and Visual Thinking & Mapping.

## License
Visual Thinking is a free and open methodology, available for anyone to use and adapt.

## Examples
Visual Thinking has been successfully applied in various contexts, including public sector innovation initiatives, such as the Accelerator Lab's work in Vietnam.
